    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-04-19T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-04-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="1093"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1093">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">102.8951: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">White</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-04-19">April 19,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>387. For Rubber Development Losa<note n="57" xml:id="d1093fn57">Otto Losa,
                        Special representative of the Rubber Development Corporation.</note> from
                        Truslow.<note n="58" xml:id="d1093fn58">Francis A. Truslow, President,
                        Rubber Development Corporation.</note> RDC rubber agreement with Peru
                    terminates December 31, 1946.<note n="59" xml:id="d1093fn59">Agreement signed
                        April 23, 1942, not printed; for negotiations, see <ref
                            target="frus1942v06#pg_665">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">vi</hi>, pp. 665</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1942v06#pg_670">670</ref>.</note> The price premium
                    agreement terminates March 31, 1946.<note n="60" xml:id="d1093fn60">The
                        agreement between the Rubber Development Corporation and the Peruvian Amazon
                        Corporation (not printed) was made by an exchange of letters dated February
                        16 and 25, 1944, and extended by a similar exchange of August 25 and 29,
                        1944. It effected a 33½% price increase.</note>
                </p>
                <p>[Here follow paragraphs the same, <hi rend="italic">mutatis mutandis</hi>, as in
                    telegram 1000 of the same date to Rio de Janeiro, printed on <ref
                        target="#pg_704">page 704</ref>.]</p>
                <p>A similar proposal is being presented to each other American country
                    participating in rubber program.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed> [Truslow] <lb/>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
